   =20
      BlackRock
   =20
 =20

The dilemma if you are BlackRock Inc. is:
=09A lot of your customers are concerned about environmental, social and go=
vernance issues, believe that the climate transition is coming, and want to=
 make green or ESG investments with a firm that cares about ESG. Also many =
politicians around the world are concerned about these issues and will appl=
y regulatory pressure to make you more ESG.=09Some of your customers, and s=
ome politicians, want the opposite: They want you to invest more in oil and=
 coal companies, they want you to oppose corporate diversity efforts, they =
are generally anti-ESG.=09You are enormous and your job is to please everyo=
ne.

I sympathize, and I do not pretend to have the answers; I don=E2=80=99t kno=
w how I would do this if I were them. My basic instinct is =E2=80=9Cbe very=
 quiet, offer=C2=A0regular funds and ESG funds and load-up-on-coal funds, a=
nd hope nobody pays too much attention=E2=80=9D; I do think that=C2=A0other=
 giant index and quasi-index managers do a better job of=C2=A0not talking s=
o much about ESG, in ways that spare them a lot of negative attention from =
both sides.
That is not BlackRock=E2=80=99s approach, though. Like the other big manage=
rs, BlackRock offers regular funds and ESG funds, and it is a huge investor=
 in oil and=C2=A0coal companies. But it also does (or, at least, did) a lot=
 of   noisy publicity around its ESG efforts, and balances it out by   some=
times doing=C2=A0noisy anti-ESG publicity:

BlackRock Inc. has named Saudi Aramco Chief Executive Officer Amin Nasser t=
o its board, underscoring the asset manager=E2=80=99s commitment to the oil=
 industry in the middle of a highly politicized debate about its role in ES=
G investing.
Nasser has led the world=E2=80=99s biggest oil producer since 2015, includi=
ng overseeing its public listing, and provides BlackRock with =E2=80=9Ca un=
ique perspective=E2=80=9D on key issues facing the company and its clients,=
 CEO Larry Fink said Monday in an emailed statement.
BlackRock and Fink, 70, have been criticized by both sides of the political=
 divide over ESG investing after promoting the strategy as a way to help th=
e global economy respond to climate change. Environmental advocates have sl=
ammed the firm for continuing to pile capital into the fossil fuel industry=
, while some Republicans have accused BlackRock of peddling a =E2=80=9Cwoke=
=E2=80=9D agenda that they say is at odds with American capitalism.
It=E2=80=99s =E2=80=9Ca very cunning move,=E2=80=9D said Sasja Beslik, chie=
f investment officer at NextGen ESG in Japan.

It is? Really? US Republican politicians are gonna be like =E2=80=9Coh, Bla=
ckRock is fine now, they have a Saudi oil executive on the board=E2=80=9D? =
Who is going to be happy with this precise combination?=C2=A0I would just=
=C2=A0not=C2=A0write a lot of letters to CEOs about how important climate c=
hange is, and also=C2=A0not=C2=A0put a Saudi oil executive on the board. Th=
e way to construct an investment-company board is not to have a bunch of cl=
imate activists and balance them with a bunch of oil executives. It=E2=80=
=99s to have a bunch of apolitical finance people and hope nobody ever both=
ers to find out who they are.
Elsewhere in BlackRock  trying to please everyone:

BlackRock will give retail investors in its biggest exchange traded fund th=
e chance to participate in proxy voting in 2024, as the $9.4tn asset manage=
r moves to rebut Republican claims that it pursues a =E2=80=9Cwoke agenda=
=E2=80=9D.
The world=E2=80=99s biggest money manager has joined fellow index fund prov=
iders State Street and Vanguard in experimenting with ways to involve ordin=
ary investors in voting on shareholder proposals at a time when their colle=
ctive influence on US companies has come under fire from both left and righ=
t.
Investors in BlackRock=E2=80=99s iShares Core S&P 500 ETF will be asked to =
choose among seven different general policies ranging from voting generally=
 with management to prioritising Catholic values or environmental, social a=
nd governance factors. Investors can also tell BlackRock to continue voting=
 their shares. Customers will not be able to cast specific votes on individ=
ual companies.

The idea is that BlackRock gives you a menu of voting=C2=A0policies, and yo=
u choose one, and then BlackRock applies that policy to do the actual votin=
g on the (hundreds and hundreds) of proposals that the fund votes on. =E2=
=80=9CThe  proposed policies are ...=C2=A0the Glass Lewis Governance Focuse=
d Policy, the ISS Board Aligned Policy, the BlackRock Investment Stewardshi=
p Policy, the Glass Lewis Benchmark Policy, the Glass Lewis Climate Policy,=
 the ISS Socially Responsible Investing Policy and the ISS Catholic Values =
Policy,=E2=80=9D and I suspect that a lot of people who distrust BlackRock=
=E2=80=99s proxy voting will also distrust the voting recommendations of th=
e big proxy advisers Glass Lewis and ISS.
Really what BlackRock should do is partner with some unexpected Republicans=
 to roll out some new proxy voting policies. Throw Donald Trump $1 million =
for 15 minutes of his time checking some boxes, and then let investors choo=
se the Donald Trump MAGA Values Policy to vote their shares. Ron DeSantis c=
ouldn=E2=80=99t criticize that! The Vivek Ramaswamy Anti-Woke=C2=A0Policy. =
The Kid Rock Proxy Voting Policy.
You don=E2=80=99t need to limit yourself to anti-ESG Republicans, either. T=
he Greta Thunberg Voting Policy. The Amin Nasser Voting Policy! The Taylor =
Swift Voting Policy. The Mr. Beast Voting Policy. Honestly this is such a g=
ood stupid idea; BlackRock should get like 30 celebrities to pick some broa=
d proxy voting guidelines and let retail customers choose their favorite ce=
lebrity to guide their shareholder voting.=C2=A0It is absolutely absolutely=
 absolutely rational for individual retail investors not to care at all how=
 their proxies are voted, their proxy votes cannot possibly matter, any ret=
ail investor who is concerned about proxy voting is concerned purely for sy=
mbolic identity reasons. Might as well market to that.

 =20
   =20
      Bank of crypto
   =20
 =20

The weird thing is, right now is a great time to be the bank of crypto. His=
torically there are two problems, in the US, with being the go-to=C2=A0bank=
 for cryptocurrency exchanges and stablecoin issuers:
=09Crypto companies had a bit of a history of lawbreaking, so you=C2=A0woul=
d want to make=C2=A0very=C2=A0sure that=C2=A0they=C2=A0were doing all the a=
ppropriate know-your-customer/anti-money-laundering checks, and not stealin=
g customer money,=C2=A0before agreeing to provide them with banking service=
s.=09Crypto prices were volatile and there was a history of =E2=80=9Cbank r=
uns=E2=80=9D in crypto, which might leave you=C2=A0vulnerable to a real ban=
k run: If a crypto exchange got $1 billion of customer money and deposited =
it in your bank, its customers might want all their money back tomorrow, wh=
ich would mean that=C2=A0you=C2=A0would have to pay back that $1 billion to=
morrow. The deposits were flighty.

I think that over time that first problem slowly solves itself: If you take=
 crypto deposits now, you are probably taking fewer deposits from criminals=
 than you were a year ago, because (1) more people in crypto are interested=
 in compliance than they used to be, (2) the crypto industry has (surprisin=
gly to me) had=C2=A0some recent litigation and legislative momentum, making=
 it all a bit less illegal and (3) a lot of last year=E2=80=99s criminals a=
re bankrupt now.
But that=E2=80=99s not the main problem that brought down the two main US c=
rypto banks,  Silvergate Capital Corp. and  Signature Bank, this March.=C2=
=A0The main problem is the second: They got all those crypto deposits, they=
 invested them in long-term loans and bonds, and then interest rates went u=
p, crypto prices went down, the deposits all vanished with the crypto crisi=
s, and the banks had to sell those loans and bonds at big losses to pay bac=
k depositors. And in fact US bank regulators were warning about that risk =
=E2=80=94=C2=A0=E2=80=9Cthe liquidity risks presented by certain sources of=
 funding from crypto-asset-related entities=E2=80=9D =E2=80=94=C2=A0in Febr=
uary; the bank regulators were concerned not about possible illegality at c=
rypto exchanges but rather about the flightiness of their deposits.
But that problem is also solved now! The basic issue for Silvergate and Sig=
nature in like 2021 was that they=C2=A0wanted to attract crypto deposits, w=
hich required a certain level of investment in technology, the Silvergate E=
xchange Network for crypto firms to pay each other, etc. But that cost mone=
y, and short-term interest rates were basically zero.
So Silvergate and Signature=C2=A0would get deposits from crypto firms and i=
nvest them in long-term bonds and loans to earn enough interest to pay for =
their businesses. And then rates went up, which had the twin effects of (1)=
 causing big losses on the banks=E2=80=99 assets and (2) crushing crypto pr=
ices and leading to big withdrawals at the worst possible time.
But now short-term interest rates are much higher. Now, if you are a US ban=
k, you can park money in reserves at the Federal Reserve and get paid 5.15%=
 interest. If you have a billion dollars of crypto deposits, you can make $=
51.5 million a year on them just by parking them at the Fed, with absolutel=
y on interest-rate or liquidity risk. In 2021, you couldn=E2=80=99t get tha=
t much interest on a 30-year mortgage. You had to take all sorts of credit =
and interest-rate risk to earn anything like 5.15% on your deposits. Now yo=
u can get that from the Fed, no problem.
Of course in 2021, if you were the bank of crypto, you did not need to pay =
any interest on deposits to=C2=A0your customers, because (1) rates were zer=
o everywhere, (2)=C2=A0they were kind of pariahs and happy to have any bank=
ing relationship and (3) they were making so much money in their business (=
and not paying any interest on deposits to=C2=A0their=C2=A0customers) that =
getting 0.25% or whatever on their deposits was not important. In 2023, if =
you are the bank of crypto =E2=80=A6=C2=A0do you have to pay interest on de=
posits? Why? Rates are higher elsewhere, but a lot of banks are still prett=
y wary of crypto, so if you=C2=A0are=C2=A0enthusiastically embracing crypto=
 customers, paying them 0% interest might still be the best they=E2=80=99re=
 going to do. And it still seems to be the norm for, for instance, stableco=
in issuers not to pay interest to their depositors, so there=E2=80=99s stil=
l some room to work with.
An offering that is like =E2=80=9Cwe will take your crypto deposits, we wil=
l not count on them staying for long, we will pay you low or no interest, a=
nd we will minimize our liquidity risk by parking all your deposits at the =
Fed=E2=80=9D would not have worked in 2021 but probably works fine in 2023.=
=C2=A0
 Anyway:

Customers Bancorp Inc. partners with hundreds of digital-asset firms, inclu=
ding major exchanges, market makers and stablecoin issuers, according to pe=
ople with knowledge of the matter. It attracted new clients after crypto-fr=
iendly lenders Silvergate Capital Corp. and Signature Bank collapsed, leavi=
ng Customers Bank =E2=80=94 the West Reading-based company=E2=80=99s primar=
y subsidiary =E2=80=94 one of a few facilitators of dollar transactions tha=
t crypto businesses could turn to.
The lender, ranked the 81st-largest US bank by assets, is now at the forefr=
ont of an industry battered by blowups, scrutinized by regulators and shunn=
ed by mainstream lenders =E2=80=94 a very different spot from almost two ye=
ars ago, when Bitcoin was at a record high and investors were piling in. Ba=
ck then, Customers Bank Chief Executive Officer Sam Sidhu touted his firm=
=E2=80=99s crypto ambitions. ...
The bank operates a payments platform that enables crypto clients to move d=
ollars with the same immediacy as crypto =E2=80=94 24 hours a day, seven da=
ys a week. Silvergate, which announced plans in March to wind down, and Sig=
nature, seized by regulators the same month, offered similar capabilities. =
Their closures =E2=80=94 which came as depositors yanked money from small l=
enders amid this year=E2=80=99s regional-bank turmoil =E2=80=94 left Custom=
ers with little competition providing such services, said Piper Sandler ana=
lyst Frank Schiraldi.
=E2=80=9CWith Signature and Silvergate basically shutting their doors, thes=
e balances had to go somewhere,=E2=80=9D he said. Customers Bank =E2=80=9Cr=
eally seems to be the last man standing.=E2=80=9D =E2=80=A6
The company decided to limit deposits on its Customers Bank Instant Token r=
eal-time payments platform, or CBIT, which caters to crypto clients, to no =
more than 15% of its total.
Deposits for CBIT held steady at about $2.25 billion at the end of the firs=
t quarter, accounting for 13% of its $17.7 billion total. That increased fr=
om $1.85 billion in mid November, following FTX=E2=80=99s collapse. ...
Customers believes it has measures in place to manage risk. For one, the ba=
nk holds CBIT deposits in US currency, as opposed to investing them in secu=
rities or loans, allowing it to expeditiously meet any withdrawal demands.

Yeah I mean that seems right: Take the money, offer real-time crypto-firm-t=
o-crypto-firm payments, and keep it all in cash earning 5.15%. And yet they=
 are uneasy:

Today, the bank is putting a cap on crypto-related deposits and Sidhu says =
the assets are just one small piece of a broader plan to expand the bank=E2=
=80=99s payments business.
Crypto =E2=80=9Cprovides a very good use case for us to prove our tech capa=
bilities=E2=80=9D for payments, Sidhu said in an interview. But Customers =
=E2=80=9Cwill be focused on the types of industries that generate us strong=
er and deeper customer relationships.=E2=80=9D

Yes, right, as a=C2=A0general=C2=A0matter,  the correct move for a regional=
 bank is to borrow short, lend long, and invest a lot in building relations=
hips with the depositors so they don=E2=80=99t all take their money out at =
once. It does seem like there=E2=80=99d be a niche for the crypto bank thou=
gh. Who cares about the relationship? It=E2=80=99s flighty money, but it=E2=
=80=99s cheap money; take it!

 =20
   =20
      X valuation
   =20
 =20

How much is Twitter worth? I guess it is called X Corp. now. Elon Musk boug=
ht it last October for about $44 billion; at the time he   said he was over=
paying. He had a few co-investors who have to report their portfolios publi=
cly, and they, uh, agree he overpaid.  Fidelity has marked down its Twitter=
 stake by almost two-thirds since the deal. And  here=E2=80=99s this:

Cathie Wood=E2=80=99s ARK Investment Management has written down its stake =
in Twitter by 47% since Elon Musk took the social-media company private las=
t year, Wood said in an interview.
=E2=80=9CWe take fair valuation very seriously and absolutely have had to w=
rite that [Twitter] down,=E2=80=9D Wood said Friday. =E2=80=9CThe write-dow=
n is not representative of our fundamental outlook and belief in the long-t=
erm return on investment we believe that it will have for our shareholders.=
=E2=80=9D
Wood is still bullish on Twitter=E2=80=99s long-term outlook. She said her =
fund updates its internal valuations of private companies frequently.
=E2=80=9CI would love to get more stock at these price levels actually, but=
 no one wants to let any go. So that tells you something,=E2=80=9D she adde=
d.

Well, what does it tell you? If Fidelity thinks that Twitter is worth $15 b=
illion, and ARK thinks that Twitter is worth $23 billion, and Fidelity owns=
 some Twitter stock and ARK wants to buy some Twitter stock, isn=E2=80=99t =
there=C2=A0a trade to be done? I mean the trade is that Fidelity sells ARK =
some Twitter stock at a $20 billion valuation; Fidelity reports a gain on t=
he sale and ARK gets stock at a discount to what it thinks is market=C2=A0v=
alue. And yet =E2=80=9Cno one wants to let any go.=E2=80=9D
There are other possible trades. A fun one is =E2=80=9CFidelity sells ARK s=
ome Twitter stock at a $30 billion valuation=E2=80=9D: Fidelity gets a big =
premium to what it thinks is market value, perhaps a big enough premium to =
induce it to do the trade, while ARK gets to mark up the rest of its Twitte=
r stake to the most recent arm=E2=80=99s-length sale price. If nobody wants=
 to let any go at a $23 billion valuation, doesn=E2=80=99t that mean it=E2=
=80=99s worth more than $23 billion?
Or here=E2=80=99s a trade  from Martin Peers at the Information:
Perhaps Musk should simply sell a few billion dollars of new Twitter shares=
 at a sharply reduced valuation level and use the money to pay off the cost=
liest bonds. Yes, he=E2=80=99d be severely diluting his own shares and thos=
e of everyone else. But that would solve some of Twitter=E2=80=99s short-te=
rm problems. For one thing, he might be able to invest money in hiring more=
 engineers so he can fix the problems with Twitter=E2=80=99s technical infr=
astructure. That in turn could change the overwhelmingly negative narrative=
 about the company right now. Otherwise, Twitter is stuck in a situation li=
ke that facing many money-losing startups, which don=E2=80=99t want to rais=
e money at a lower valuation than their 2021 peak but can=E2=80=99t afford =
not to. Those startups will have to eventually bite the bullet on valuation=
. The same applies to Musk=E2=80=99s Twitter.
I am not sure =E2=80=9CElon Musk bought Twitter for $44 billion and is now =
selling it off for $20 billion=E2=80=9D would change the narrative all that=
 much, but I am also not sure he=E2=80=99d have to go that low.
Ed Hammond   wrote in June that Musk should just take Twitter public again,=
 and I am increasingly   coming around to that view, mainly because it woul=
d be the funniest possible outcome.
  [2]
 The problem for Musk is:
=09He is very very good at attracting fans who trust him implicitly and wil=
l invest in his companies at high valuations, but=09Twitter is not doing so=
 hot right now, =09=09cash-flow-wise.

If Twitter is a private company and you own almost all of the equity, you a=
re mainly exposed to its=C2=A0cash flows, not the=C2=A0meme potential of it=
s stock. If you take it public and sell a bunch of stock to your ardent fan=
s, the business results matter less, and your ability to attract attention =
matters more. Surely, given the facts here,=C2=A0that increases the valuati=
on?

