   =20
      Typo leak
   =20
 =20

If you have some secret information that you want to communicate to the US =
Army, I guess you would email it to, like, tips@army.mil?
  [3]
 But if instead you email it to tips@army.ml, a one-letter difference, it=
=E2=80=99ll go to Russia?

Millions of US military emails have been misdirected to Mali through a =E2=
=80=9Ctypo leak=E2=80=9D that has exposed highly sensitive information, inc=
luding diplomatic documents, tax returns, passwords and the travel details =
of top officers.
Despite repeated warnings over a decade, a steady flow of email traffic con=
tinues to the .ML domain, the country identifier for Mali, as a result of p=
eople mistyping .MIL, the suffix to all US military email addresses.
The problem was first identified almost a decade ago by Johannes Zuurbier, =
a Dutch internet entrepreneur who has a contract to manage Mali=E2=80=99s c=
ountry domain. ...
Control of the .ML domain will revert on Monday from Zuurbier to Mali=E2=80=
=99s government, which is closely allied with Russia. When Zuurbier=E2=80=
=99s 10-year management contract expires, Malian authorities will be able t=
o gather the misdirected emails. The Malian government did not respond to r=
equests for comment.

=E2=80=9CMuch of the email flow is spam and none is marked as classified,=
=E2=80=9D and apparently if you work in the US=C2=A0military and you email =
someone else in the US=C2=A0military, the system prevents this typo. But if=
 you are an outside contractor, or an Army officer emailing from your perso=
nal account, all bets are off. =E2=80=9CAround a dozen people mistakenly re=
quested recovery passwords for an intelligence community system to be sent =
to Mali.=E2=80=9D

