<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The weird thing is, right now is a great time =
to be the bank of crypto. Historically there are two problems, in the US, w=
ith being the go-to=C2=A0bank for cryptocurrency exchanges and stablecoin i=
ssuers:</p>
<ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;"=
>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Crypto companies had a bit of a histo=
ry of lawbreaking, so you=C2=A0would want to make=C2=A0<em>very=C2=A0</em>s=
ure that=C2=A0<em>they=C2=A0</em>were doing all the appropriate know-your-c=
ustomer/anti-money-laundering checks, and not stealing customer money,=C2=
=A0before agreeing to provide them with banking services.</li>=09<li style=
=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Crypto prices were volatile and there was a histor=
y of =E2=80=9Cbank runs=E2=80=9D in crypto, which might leave <em>you=C2=A0=
</em>vulnerable to a real bank run: If a crypto exchange got $1 billion of =
customer money and deposited it in your bank, its customers might want all =
their money back tomorrow, which would mean that=C2=A0<em>you=C2=A0</em>wou=
ld have to pay back that $1 billion tomorrow. The deposits were flighty.</l=
i>
</ol>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I think that over time that first problem slow=
ly solves itself: If you take crypto deposits now, you are probably taking =
fewer deposits from criminals than you were a year ago, because (1) more pe=
ople in crypto are interested in compliance than they used to be, (2) the c=
rypto industry has (surprisingly to me) had=C2=A0some recent litigation and=
 legislative momentum, making it all a bit less illegal and (3) a lot of la=
st year=E2=80=99s criminals are bankrupt now.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But that=E2=80=99s not the main problem that b=
rought down the two main US crypto banks, <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloo=
mbergbusiness.com/click/32118824.260407/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9=
